## Migration: Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Problem

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006). Your code uses three removed APIs:
- `Thread.Abort()` — force-kills thread
- `catch (ThreadAbortException)` — cleanup on abort
- `Thread.ResetAbort()` — prevent rethrow

### Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `ProcessLoop` while loop | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationToken` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | `token.IsCancellationRequested` check |
| `_workerThread.Abort()` in `Stop()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token to unblock waits
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Clean up partial work (migrated from ThreadAbortException handler)
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed — we simply continue to the loop check
                // which will exit because token is cancelled
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Give the thread time to finish gracefully
        _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));

        // If still alive after timeout, there's no Thread.Abort equivalent.
        // The thread will exit at its next cancellation checkpoint.
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

### Key Changes to Supporting Methods

```csharp
// BEFORE: may block indefinitely with no way to cancel
private Item GetNextItem() { /* blocking call */ }

// AFTER: pass token so blocking can be interrupted
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    // Replace Thread.Sleep with cancellation-aware wait
    // Replace queue.Take() with queue.Take(token)
    // Replace WaitHandle.WaitOne() with:
    //   WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { handle, token.WaitHandle });
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    // ...
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **`GetNextItem` still blocks** | If it doesn't accept/check the token, `Stop()` hangs forever. The token must reach every blocking call. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. Always `Dispose()`. |
| **Expecting immediate stop** | Cooperative cancellation only works at checkpoints. Long-running `ProcessItem` won't stop mid-operation unless it also checks the token. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not unrelated ones. |
| **Removing cleanup logic** | The `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` from the old `ThreadAbortException` handler is critical — it moved into the `OperationCanceledException` handler. Don't lose it. |

### Fundamental Paradigm Shift

**.NET Framework:** Runtime forcibly injects `ThreadAbortException` at any point → code is interrupted whether it cooperates or not.

**.NET 8:** Code must **voluntarily** check `CancellationToken` and throw/exit. If `ProcessItem` runs for 10 minutes without checking the token, cancellation waits 10 minutes. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular intervals inside long operations.
